T1  - LONG-TERM CARE AND FAMILY BARGAINING*
AU  - ENGERS, MAXIM
AU  - STERN1, STEVEN
Y1  - 2002/02/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.t01-1-00004
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 73
EP  - 114
VL  - 43
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.t01-1-00004
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We present a structural model of how families decide who should care for elderly parents. We use data from the National Long-Term Care Survey to estimate and test the parameters of the model. Then we use the parameter estimates to simulate the effects of the existing long-term trends in terms of the common but untested explanations for them. Finally, we simulate the effects of alternative family bargaining rules on individual utility to measure the sensitivity of our results to the family decision-making assumptions we make.
ER  - 

