T1  - A MATCHING MODEL WITH ENDOGENOUS SKILL REQUIREMENTS>*
AU  - ALBRECHT, JAMES
AU  - VROMAN1, SUSAN
Y1  - 2002/02/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.t01-1-00012
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 283
EP  - 305
VL  - 43
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.t01-1-00012
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We consider a labor market in which workers differ in their abilities and jobs differ in their skill requirements. The distribution of worker abilities is exogenous, but we model the choice of skill requirements by firms. High-skill jobs produce more output than low-skill jobs, but high-skill jobs require high-skill workers and thus are more difficult to fill. We use a matching model together with a Nash bargaining approach to wage setting to determine the equilibrium mix of job types, along with the equilibrium relationship between worker and job characteristics, wages, and unemployment.
ER  - 
